@node Introduction
@next "BH6dox"
@prev Main

	#include @{"<standard/disclaimer>" link Disclaimer}     /* It's so easy if you know C */

	When I bought my A4000 I was disappointed when I saw that some
	of my favourite software seemed not to work under AGA. I thought
	about fixing it, but soon I realized it need some more work and
	started to examine some code. One result is this tool.

	The BitplaneRipper is (strongly) based on the BitplaneHacker V6.0
	by Christoph Soukup alias Spike of S!P / TRSI in 1991. You can read
	his @{"BplHackerV6.0 Docs" link "BH6dox"} for the main features.

	Read the @{"New Features" link "New Features"} and/or the @{History link history} text to see what I have
	fixed/added/changed in the original program and what is still to do.
	I think I have done a lot on the original code not to be called a
	lamer who ripped someone's code. Anyway I wouldn't care at all. I
	gained new motivation when I read a request for such a tool in the
	news on internet.

	This BitplaneRipper won't work on OCS/ECS computers and on systems
	with graphic hardware who don't support a LoadView(NULL) to reset
	the display. This tool was developed on a A4000/030 but should
	work at least on all other (standard) AGA platforms.
@{i}
	NOTE:	Fastmem isn't really required, but strongly recommended
		preventing the Chipmem getting overlayed by the Ripper's
		public data hunks.
@{ui}
	I'm always searching for software supporting AGA and patched old
	incompatible programs. Feel free to send stuff to my @{"(e-mail) address" link Credits}.

@endnode

@node "BH6dox"
@next "New Features"
@prev Introduction


	   @{b}NOTE:@{ub} Features that have changed are written @{i}italic@{ui} !

	    changes are explained in the @{"New Features" link "New Features"} section.

	@{u}                                                          @{uu}


	     Welcome to BPLhacker v6.0 (512k ChipMem version)
	       (req.library - Filerequester is implemented)

		      Coding & Gfx-design by SPIKE of

	    SURPRISE! Productions / Tristar & RedSector in 1991

	(Instructions are below)

	Well, well with Action Replay II you can rip every picture but
	it is very expensive and has not so many functions as
	the BPLhacker!

	Everyone in may copy this tool but it is prophibited to sell
	BPLhacker for money. Firms which want to release and sell this
	cool product have to contact me (Adress below).

	If you have some suggestions or bug-reports or if you just want
	to contact me then write to:

		Surprise! Productions
		Christoph Soukup
		Hardeggasse 67/12/3
		A-1220 Vienna / Austria / Earth

		Ph#:  +43 - 222 - 220341
		Fax#: +43 - 222 - 2203412


	And now the instructions...

	<ESC>...............Exit BPLHACKER

	<ARROWS>............Scroll enabled bitplanes slow
	<SHIFT>+<ARROWS>....Scroll enabled bitplanes fast

@{i}	<1>-<6>.............Select number of bitplanes
	<F1>-<F6>...........Enable/disable bitplanes for scroll
	<SHIFT>+<F1>-<F6>...Enable only this bitplane for scroll
	<F7>................Enable all bitplanes for scrolling
	<SHIFT>+<F7>........Disable all bitplanes for scrolling@{ui}

	<L> / <H>...........Set gfx-mode: LORES/HIRES
@{i}	<F8>................Set gfx-mode: EHB or HAM (only at 6 bpls)@{ui}
	<DEL>...............Reset modulo & screen-width
	<BACKSPACE>.........Set all bitplanes to adress of first bpl
	<SHIFT>+<HELP>......Reset all settings to standard

	<[> / <]>...........Change modulo -/+         (num-keyboard)
	</> / <*>...........Change screen-width -/+   (num-keyboard)
	<+> / <->...........Change save-height +/-    (num-keyboard)

	<SHIFT>+<RETURN>....Select only second bitplane for moving...
	<RETURN>............Auto-bitplane-overlay
		   Example: You have found 3 bitplanes in memory and
			    you want to merge all them to a three-
			    -bitplane-screen, so move bpl2 over bpl1
			    (use upper function) and press <RETURN>
			    (just discover yourself how it works...)

	<SPACE>.............Search colors for current pic
	                    (use it several times for the best result)
	<SHIFT>+<SPACE>.....Set standard cyan-palette for pic

	<S>.................Save whole pic as IFF to disk
	<SHIFT>+<S>.........Save only the visible pic as IFF to disk

@{i}	Attention: with only 512kB you might get problems at saving,
		   because the save-buffer could destroy the pics
@{ui}
	<M>.................Set modulo for blitter-format-pics (=BFP)
			    (Please set first the number of bitplanes
			    and set screen-width to width of one bpl)
	<.>.................Move right bpl over left bpl (for BFP)
	<,>.................Move left bpl over right bpl (for BFP)
	<R>.................Remap bitplanes: first becomes last etc.

	<RIGHT-AMIGA>.......Search for further non-zero gfxdata

	<T>.................Take save-height from ruler-size
	<F9>................Change palette for menu
	<F10>...............Hide / show menu (like in DPaint)

	Move mouse up/down to change ruler-position and hold down
	the right button to resize the ruler.
@endnode

@node "New Features"
@next History
@prev "BH6dox"

			       @{b}@{u}New Features@{uu}@{ub}

	<1>-<8>.............Select number of bitplanes
	<F1>-<F8>...........Enable/disable bitplanes for scroll
	<SHIFT>+<F1>-<F8>...Enable only this bitplane for scroll

	<9>.................Enable all bitplanes for scrolling
	<SHIFT>+<9>.........Disable all bitplanes for scrolling

	<0>.................Set other gfx-modes: EHB or HAM (only at 6/8 bpls)

	<P>.................Show 256 colour palette

	<SHIFT>+<HELP>......Jump to the middle of chipmem
			    ($100000 if you have 2MB Chipmem)

@endnode

@node History
@next Credits
@prev "New Features"

@{b}@{u}			BitplaneRipper History@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}@{u}V6.13@{uu}@{ub}

04-Jun-95	-finished @{b}1st release version@{ub} (v6.13beta)
28-Apr-95	-now hires pictures with more than 4 planes are shown
		 correctly

12-Apr-95	-some fixes in the save routine (for EHB/HAM, interleaved gfx)
14-Apr-95	-now skipping all 24bit colour banks

09-Apr-95	-save routine rewritten (now depth dynamic)
		*@{b}It happened! 1st working AGA version finished. Phew!@{ub}
08-Apr-95	-changed to smaller font (6 pts)
		+merged both copperlist into a big one (view palette with 'P')
01-Apr-95	+several changes for new screen mode handling (ehb/ham)

18-Mar-95	+changed copper list for 8bit support

14-Mar-95	+added string support			[24932 bytes]

13-Mar-95	-improving the hex/dec number output routines
		 (yeah, I'm using now a real font)	[25052 bytes]

10/11-Mar-95	+added AGA palette detection
		 (8 color banks, selection via BPLCON3, hope this works)
		-further optimizing the data model	[25228 bytes]
@rem"            (joining the bss and the data area to one big data hunk"
@rem"             reduced the relocations from 375 to 31 in code section)"

05/06-Mar-95	-optimizing all data access by using 'small data model'
@rem"            23624 bytes --> 22132 bytes (1 BSS & 1 Data Segment)"

03-Mar-95	+Bugfix: grabbing all Workbench input via input handler
		 (so you cannot click around on WB Screen while ripping),
		 but all key/mouse input still read by using the hardware.

@{b}@{u}V6.12@{uu}@{ub}

25-Jan-95	+improved the (lame) IFF save routine
		 (no more using a copybuffer, now saves directly to disk)

14/15-Jan-95	+created new 'GUI' (now Hires) with more information

08-Jan-95	+with Shift+Help you can now jump to the middle of chipmem
		 (Usually I load a prog to $100000 and use this function
		  to get there and avoid long scroll time when ripping sth.)

		-removed online help to save more chipmem (read docs instead!)

@{b}@{u}V6.11@{uu}@{ub}

 1/1995		-using the nice reqtools.library (the best!)
		-installed systemfriendly interrupt using AddIntServer
		-now the ripper checks installed chipmem size via MaxLocMem
		 (some A4000's were sold with only 1MB chipmem equipped)

@{b}@{u}V6.10@{uu}@{ub}

 1/1995		started major recoding
		-improved the startup code

 9/1994		abandoned the project for unknown time

 8/1994		disassembled BitplaneHacker6.0
		-changed handling of gfx & copperlists
		-fixed bug (6th plane wasn't saved)
		-added startup code for AGA compatibility
		-optimized the code here and there
		-increased chipmem range to 1MB
		 (at this time my A4000 had only 1MB chipmem :-( )


@{b}some things to do:@{ub}

	- new feature: saving palette (iff and/or raw)
	- possibility to specify address for palette searching
	  (useful to skip some big copperlists! I hate chunky-copper ;-)
	- clear memory segments
	- command/status line
	- @{b}It's up to you. Give Bugreports and Ideas for new features
	  to the @{" author " link Credits}.@{ub}

@{b}known bugs:@{ub}

	- BplRipper surely wont work with graphic cards and/or new hires
	  screen modes (read @{"Introduction" link "Introduction"} for further info)
	  @{i}I will see if I can at least do something for all you Multiscan
	  Monitor owners. What a pity I don't own one.@{ui} :( :( :(
@endnode


